1 Summary

During this project, we will explore a car database in order to evaluate whether an automatic or a manual transmission is better as car gaz consumption is concerned. To do so, we will review the relationship between a set of variables and miles per gallon (MPG) by fitting multiple regression models. Then we will evaluate the relevant model fit by looking at residuals in order to optimize the model accuracy and by looking for potential outliers. Finally, we will quantify the MPG difference between automatic and manual transmissions.

2 Exploratory analysis

data("mtcars")
library(ggplot2)

2.1 Testing for automatic and manual transmission mean difference

t<-t.test(x = mtcars[mtcars$am==1,"mpg"],y= mtcars[mtcars$am==0,"mpg"],paired = FALSE)
t
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  mtcars[mtcars$am == 1, "mpg"] and mtcars[mtcars$am == 0, "mpg"]
## t = 3.7671, df = 18.332, p-value = 0.001374
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##   3.209684 11.280194
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  24.39231  17.14737

From figure 5.1 and t-test above, we can definitely tell that mpg increase for automatic cars lies between 3.2096842 and 11.2801944 with 95% confidence.

Model 6 am beta estimate fails to reject null hyp, thus we will carry on with model 5 which is the better compromise between RSS and am beta estimate, meaning automatic cars increase mpg by 5.2770853 (which lies in the 95% confident range computed previously). It should be noted that, r-squared is 0.7820346 which is a pretty reliable regression.

3.3 Residuals review

Before validating the model above, let’s review the residuals and check for potential outliers.

# plot(fit5)
fits<-dffits(fit5)
betas<-dfbetas(fit5)[,2]
hats<-hatvalues(fit5)

hats_outliers<-hats>.15
ggplot()+
  geom_point(aes(x = fit5$fitted.values, y=hats, color=(hats_outliers)))+
  geom_text(
    aes(x = fit5$fitted.values[hats_outliers], y=hats[hats_outliers]),
    label=names(fit5$fitted.values[hats_outliers]),
    nudge_x = 0.1, nudge_y = 0.1,
    size=2
  )+
  labs(title="Residual leverage")+
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5)
    )+
  scale_colour_manual(values=c("blue", "salmon"))

betas_outliers<-betas>.4
ggplot()+
  geom_point(aes(x = fit5$fitted.values, y=betas, color=(betas_outliers)))+
  geom_text(
    aes(x = fit5$fitted.values[betas_outliers], y=betas[betas_outliers]),
    label=names(fit5$fitted.values[betas_outliers]),
    nudge_x = 0.1, nudge_y = 0.1,
    size=2
  )+
  labs(title="Beta influence")+
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5)
    )+
  scale_colour_manual(values=c("blue", "salmon"))

fits_outliers<-fits>.5
ggplot()+
  geom_point(aes(x = fit5$fitted.values, y=fits, color=(fits_outliers)))+
  geom_text(
    aes(x = fit5$fitted.values[fits_outliers], y=fits[fits_outliers]),
    label=names(fit5$fitted.values[fits_outliers]),
    nudge_x = 0.1, nudge_y = 0.1,
    size=2
  )+
  labs(title="Fit influence")+
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5)
    )+
  scale_colour_manual(values=c("blue", "salmon"))

From the charts above, we note that - Maserati Bora and Ford Pantera are the most levered data points - Maserati Bora, Lotus Europa and Toyota Corolla are the most influent points beta wise - Maserati Bora, Lotus Europa and Toyota Corolla are the most sensitive predicted values

As a result, we will consider Maserati Bora and Toyota Corolla as outliers hereafter.

#remove potential outliers and assess regression error
library(car)
## Loading required package: carData
mtcarsNo<-mtcars[-which.names(names =c("Maserati Bora", "Toyota Corolla"),object = mtcars),]

fitNo<-lm(formula = mpg~am+hp,data = mtcarsNo)
summary(fitNo)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = mpg ~ am + hp, data = mtcarsNo)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -3.9351 -2.4641  0.2883  1.5324  5.9839 
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 27.221909   1.575272  17.281 3.99e-16 ***
## am           4.297659   1.101218   3.903 0.000572 ***
## hp          -0.062862   0.009047  -6.948 1.82e-07 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 2.684 on 27 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.7855, Adjusted R-squared:  0.7696 
## F-statistic: 49.45 on 2 and 27 DF,  p-value: 9.406e-10

After removal of Toyota Corolla and Maseratti Bora considered as outliers, am beta estimate p value is lower than 5%, then we reject the Null hypothesis i.e. accepting am beta estimate value. Residual standard error is down from to 2.684 from 2.909 before outliers removal.

4 Conclusion

From the regression model without outliers, the difference in intercept is the mpg difference between automatic and manual transmission. Thus automatic cars mpg is 4.3 mpg higher than manual cars.
